  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970\n- Requires financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Mandates reporting of cash transactions over $10,000\n\n2. Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Made money laundering a federal criminal offense\n- Established criminal penalties for money laundering activities\n\n3. Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1988\n- Expanded money laundering provisions\n- Increased penalties for drug-related money laundering\n\n4. Money Laundering Suppression Act of 1994\n- Enhanced requirements for reporting suspicious activities\n- Increased regulatory oversight of financial institutions\n\n5. USA PATRIOT Act of 2001\n- Significantly strengthened anti-money laundering regulations\n- Increased information sharing between financial institutions and law enforcement\n\n6. Corporate Transparency Act of 2021\n- Requires reporting of beneficial ownership information\n- Aims to prevent money laundering through shell companies\n\nThese statutes collectively provide a comprehensive legal framework for detecting, preventing, and prosecuting money laundering activities in the United States.",
